S'[[<p class="css-jwz2nf etfikam0"><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Producer/Director </strong>Suzanne Hillinger</p>, <p class="css-jwz2nf etfikam0">Join the conversation about The Times\\u2019s new TV show with @theweekly on <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://twitter.com/theweekly" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="">Twitter</a> and <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.instagram.com/theweekly/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="">Instagram</a>. </p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0"></p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">How does a New York City taxi driver who makes about $22,000 a year get a loan for almost $1 million? <!-- -->Our reporters investigating the taxi industry for \\u201cThe Weekly\\u201d found that <!-- -->a group of under-regulated industry leaders created a financial bubble in the market for medallions, the permits that let drivers own their own cab. Bankers, brokers, fleet owners and even city officials artificially inflated the prices of medallions and reaped huge profits by steering immigrant drivers into reckless loans.</p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">After The Times first published its investigation in May 2019, various government officials vowed to take action. </p>, <p class="css-15hwz5e evys1bk0">The city is investigating the brokers.</p>, <p class="css-15hwz5e evys1bk0">The state has begun an inquiry into the lenders.</p>, <p class="css-15hwz5e evys1bk0">The <!-- -->federal government<!-- --> is reviewing some of the regulators.</p>, <p class="css-15ngikh evys1bk0"><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Brian M. Rosentha</strong>l is an investigative reporter on the Metro Desk. A Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist, he uses data, documents and interviews to expose problems in New York. He\\u2019s most passionate about telling the stories of vulnerable people in society. Follow Brian on Twitter: <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://twitter.com/brianmrosenthal" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">@brianmrosenthal</a></p>, <p class="css-15ngikh evys1bk0"><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Emma G. Fitzsimmons </strong>covers transportation for the Metro desk. She writes about the ways New Yorkers get around the city \\u2014 above and below ground. Her reporting has focused on the decline of mass transit and the rapid rise of ride-hailing apps like Uber. Follow Emma on Twitter: <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://twitter.com/emmagf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">@emmgf</a></p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0"></p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Mohammad Hossain, one of the drivers featured in the show, and his family watched the episode with Brian and Suzanne at Times headquarters. </p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">After the episode, Emma called cabby Nicolae Hent, who lost his fellow colleague and friend to suicide last year. </p>, <p class="css-jwz2nf etfikam0">Brian, Emma, and Suzanne give us the latest update on the people you saw on this episode of \\u201cThe Weekly.\\u201d </p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0"></p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">State and city leaders are <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/20/nyregion/nyc-taxi-medallion-loans-attorney-general.html?module=inline" title="">investigating the taxi crisis</a> and discussing several different solutions to help drivers, including a bailout of their loans and changing how the loans are regulated. Some lawmakers are <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/policy/infrastructure/how-new-york-could-respond-to-taxi-medallion-lending-crisis.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title="">crafting legislation</a> to address issues identified by the Times investigation.</p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Several city councilmembers say the city should take responsibility for its role in driving medallion sales. They are working on a bill that would allow the city to buy medallion loans from lenders and forgive much of the debt.</p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">New Yorkers often ask Emma Fitzsimmons, the transit reporter for The Times, how they can help taxi drivers and if they should delete Uber or Lyft, the popular ride-hail apps. It\\u2019s a complicated issue, she said, and there\\u2019s no easy answer. But one thing definitely helps: Tip your driver.</p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Whether you hail a taxi or order an Uber, your driver often works long hours and spends a lot on expenses such as gas and insurance. Taxi and app drivers are both <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/17/nyregion/uber-taxi-drivers-struggle.html?module=inline" title="">struggling financially</a>. The <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/02/travel/should-you-tip-your-uber-driver-if-so-how-much.html?module=inline" title="">tip goes directly to drivers</a> and helps them support their families. </p>, <p class="css-1n5vg1k">Behind-the-scenes commentary about this episode, \\u201cThe Myth of the Medallion\\u201d</p>, <p>Through this monitor, producer and director Suzanne Hillinger watched reporter Brian Rosenthal on a shoot. Brian said, \\u201cI\\u2019ve never been on television before, so it was definitely a new experience. I tried to pretend that the camera was not there, and just act naturally. Somehow, I made it through.\\u201d</p>, <p>Transit reporter Emma Fitzsimmons said it\\u2019s \\u201cdifficult to be discreet\\u201d with a camera crew following her around. \\u201cWhen we went to the taxi lot at JFK Airport, suddenly I was surrounded by drivers, all wanting to share their story.\\u201d</p>, <p>New York City issued the first taxi medallions in 1937 for $10 apiece. For decades, their value slowly climbed. Then, between 2002 and 2014, the price skyrocketed \\u2014 from $200,000 dollars to $1.2 million. The medallion was seen as a safe investment, but the truth is, many people who spread the myth of the medallion had an incentive for the prices to go up forever.\\xa0</p>, <p>Larry Fisher was a chief loan officer at Melrose Credit Union, a major taxi lender, from 2003 \\u2014 2016. At the height of the bubble, the company collected $80 million in interest and fees every year. Mr. Fisher said, \\u201cSo many people have gone bankrupt\\u2026 I feel badly about it, but what has kept me sane is that I\\u2019m not the only one who was involved.\\u201d</p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The episode features Brian\\u2019s investigation of the <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/19/nyregion/nyc-taxis-medallions-suicides.html?module=inline" title="">reckless loans that \\u201cdevastated a generation of taxi drivers</a>.\\u201d Taxi medallions were once considered a safe investment. <!-- -->Now they sell for a fraction of the record price.<!-- --> Read parts <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/19/nyregion/nyc-taxis-medallions-suicides.html?module=inline" title="">one</a> and <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/19/nyregion/taxi-medallions.html?module=inline" title="">two</a>.</p>, <p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Mohammad emptied his savings to buy a taxi medallion. He had no idea that he had just signed away his financial freedom. Watch this clip of \\u201cThe Weekly.\\u201d </p>, <p class="css-15hwz5e evys1bk0">It took a year, <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/22/reader-center/taxi-medallion-investigation.html?rref=collection%2Fbyline%2Fbrian-m.-rosenthal&amp;action=click&amp;contentCollection=undefined&amp;region=stream&amp;module=stream_unit&amp;version=latest&amp;contentPlacement=1&amp;pgtype=collection" title="">450 interviews and a database</a> built from scratch to answer a simple question: Why had anyone ever agreed to pay $1 million for the right to drive a yellow cab?</p>, <p class="css-15hwz5e evys1bk0">Emma reports on the <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/02/nyregion/taxi-drivers-suicide-nyc.html" title="">suicides of several New York City taxi drivers</a>. She breaks down what the city\\u2019s taxi commissioner, Meera Joshi, characterizes as an epidemic. </p>, <p class="css-15hwz5e evys1bk0"><em class="css-2fg4z9 e1gzwzxm0">If you are having thoughts of suicide, call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-8255 (TALK) or go to </em><a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.speakingofsuicide.com/resources" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" title=""><em class="css-2fg4z9 e1gzwzxm0">SpeakingOfSuicide.com/resources</em></a><em class="css-2fg4z9 e1gzwzxm0"> for a list of additional resources. Here\\u2019s what you can do when a loved one is severely depressed.</em></p>, <p class="css-jwz2nf etfikam0"><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Director of Photography</strong> Adam Beckman<br/><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Video Editor</strong> Pierre Takal<br/><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Story Editors </strong>Dan Barry, Liz O. Baylen, Liz Day, Alexandra Garcia<br/><strong class="css-8qgvsz ebyp5n10">Associate Producer</strong> Madeline Rosenberg </p>]]'
